<br>
Using the above setup (WinXP using Internet Connection Sharing and Firewall, Everquest on a client behind it) I go linkdead while zoning and at other random occasions.<br>
<br>
In the days of Win98 and ME, you could use some third party software to unblock ports 1024-9000 UDP, which would clear up the problem.<br>
<br>
In Win2000 and XP though, you can't use this software, and their extremely simple system only allows you to explicitly forward ports (rather than just unblock them) and only specify the ports <b><i>one at a time</b></i>.  So as you can imagine, opening port 1024, 1025....9000 would be quite a task!<br>
<br>
I'd rather not take the firewall down altogether - I'd at least like it there for ports below 1024.<br>
<br>
Anyone know an easy way to do this?<br>
<br>
(Yeah I know, set up a FreeBSD or Linux routing box.  But I need to use ICS as it's the only thing that will work with both of my parents' Gamevoice clients at once)<br>
<br>
